Ulaire Nelya, Ringwraith in Twilight x3<br>
<a href="javascript:card_browser(128)">Ulaire Toldea, Messenger of Morgul</a> x2<br>
Can You Protect Me From Yourself? x4<br>
Saruman&#8217;s Power x2<br>
<a href="javascript:card_browser(113)">Nazgul Sword</a> x2<br>
<a href="javascript:card_browser(89)">Relentless</a> Charge x4<br>
<a href="javascript:card_browser(863)">Their Power Is in Terror</a> x3<br>
Too Great and Terrible x3<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
    </FONT></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font class="h2font"> Strategy</Font></TD><TD> </TD></TR><TR><TD COLSPAN="2" VALIGN="TOP"><font class="bfont"> This is a much-revised version of my first post-Elf Lords deck &#8220;Gandalf&#8217;s Trusted Wisdom.&#8221; I tried to make it fairly original and extremely effective. For the fellowship, I decided to shift the focus off Aragorn and onto Legolas, and now that I have all the cards I need, I&#8217;ve rebuilt the shadow to combat the new strategies that have become so popular. I know this is a long strategy section, but try to hear me out. I&#8217;ve got pretty good reasons for everything.  <br>
<br>
<br>
THE ARCHER FORMERLY KNOWN AS PRINCE<br>
<br>
Or is it the other way around? Legolas had some of the best moves in the movie (precise shots, double shots, far shots, walking a top drifting snow, amazing whirling knives, and my personal favorite: the shot/shot/arrow-stab to the eye of an Uruk/nock/draw/fire at another Uruk) so I was a little disappointed at his stats for the card game. They just didn&#8217;t seem worthy of an elf prince. And the only weapon that he could carry was a great special ability bow that was tough to activate . . . until now. For those of you tired of focusing on archery, The Long-knives of Legolas has got to be one of the best possible values in Middle-Earth weaponry. This 1-cost +3 (essentially) makes the Prince of Mirkwood a 9 (Ok, not EXACTLY but I&#8217;m trying to simplify here) vs. anyone but the Cave Troll, the Balrog and Bill Ferny. Granted, these are important exceptions (the first two anyway) but aided by the powers of the Bow and Arwen&#8217;s trusty steed, Legolas is going to add an archery wound every battle, win a skirmish or two (in this case, a FIERCE Enquea can actually be a good thing) wound another minion or two with the bow after winning those skirmishes, and the coup-de-gras, the little used (until now) card known as Dismay Our Enemies! After causing 3-5 wounds all by himself, he may discard another minion entirely! Nothing left but Lurtz, the Balrog, the Cave Troll, or the Witch King? Not enough twilight to remove 3? Too bad! So without a single exertion (sorry A Ranger&#8217;s Versatility &#8211; alas I knew thee well . . .) and counting only 1 point of archery, Legolas still takes out up to 10 vitality in a single battle? Hey, it could happen! It could even be MORE with multiple Dismays . . . Oh, and one more thing about the Long-knives. The &#8211;2 IS important at times. Take a Troop of Uruk-hai, for example. It cancels the +1 but not the &#8211;2. Since Asfaloth isn&#8217;t a weapon, it&#8217;s 8 to 7, in favor of Legolas!<br>
<br>
Ok, so maybe Legolas can&#8217;t protect Frodo all by himself. So . . . Gimli, Son of Gloin begins the adventure with him. He can pump and cause 2 wounds without help from anything, gets really buff and resilient with his gear, and can cause three wounds to the minion he beats then chip in an extra wound on another orc when he wins with his axe. Not bad for another 2-cost companion, eh? But not enough, you say? Allright, as long as Gandalf isn&#8217;t TOO late, he comes in a 9/4 and just gets tougher with his gear. &#8220;Trust Me . . .&#8221; he says. Ok, I do. I&#8217;m a believer! You &#8216;da man, er . . . wizard, Gandalf! With three Gandalf signets to spot already, winning skirmishes against this fellowship is tough indeed. Remember the Troop example earlier? So the Troop pumps, so can Legolas now. Even Frodo can win, or at least not be overwhelmed. Oh, but what about all that twilight being made by all that gear? The answer? Gandalf&#8217;s Wisdom. Most of the 1-cost items will end up costing nothing, and 2-cost items like Gimli&#8217;s Axe, Asfaloth, Glamdring and Gandalf&#8217;s Staff could end up being free as well. Sting and Glamdring can help with twilight too, but I&#8217;ll probably save Gandalf&#8217;s vitality for Trust Me exertions. I&#39;ll generally save Dismays for times when there isn&#39;t 3 twilight to remove, but if I&#39;ve drawn into all 3 and I&#39;m double moving, I&#39;ll go ahead and use one on a not as worthy minion to try for the twilight reduction and save a wound at the same time.   <br>
<br>
And what about Aragorn? He&#8217;s really just there to die gloriously in a swarm, if necessary, and to temporarily give the illusion that he&#8217;s a lynchpin. Who travels with 5 companions these days, anyway, right? He does boost Gandalf&#8217;s strength one more point, however, and if something unfortunate should happen to somebody else, I&#8217;m still very much in the game even with an unarmed Aragorn out. He also helps with Silverlode Banks, so I won&#8217;t be THAT eager to get him killed, I just won&#8217;t let it get to me. At any rate, skirmish order is everything with this deck, so I&#8217;ll be paying a lot of attention to which one to do first. This deck can turn a swarm into a splat pretty quick if things are handled in the right order.<br>
<br>
Elrond and Ottar provide throughput and gear-doubles/shadow-clog discard, and, in Elrond&#8217;s case, condition removal. I won&#8217;t be greedy and exert Elrond more than once a turn (unless it&#8217;s my last move) and I won&#8217;t use him to draw on the same turn I plan on using a Sentinels. The last thing I want is for the oft-present Tower Assassin to take him out. Gil-Galad and Endurance give my main guys some extra cushion versus Relentless Charge or Damage +1, and if things get really close they can be discarded for the extra strength. Gimli&#8217;s Helm can, of course, be a lifesaver when he gets out-pumped, and there&#8217;s often a Beyond the Height of Men looming. That&#8217;s why there are two. There are two of a lot of things, but they&#8217;re all important. Getting set up quickly is no trouble that way, and there may be times when Cantea&#39;s ability is just unavoidable. 26 of the 36 fellowship cards in the draw deck are IMMEDIATELY playable (I don&#8217;t need to spot Gandalf for either of his conditions). This was part of my goal in getting away from Aragorn. I&#8217;ll only bid 1 and will go second if given the choice. Going second often denies me the Pony, and I hate Aragorn-clog with a passion. Problem solved. I&#8217;ll usually double to 3, single to 4, double to 6, then see what&#8217;s happening. This fellowship isn&#8217;t any faster than normal. It usually needs the sanctuaries, but so does just about every fellowship. It isn&#8217;t slow, either. It&#8217;s steady. It&#8217;s solid. It protects the Ring-bearer. It gets there first partly because of the power of . . .<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
DE-EVOLUTION<br>
<br>
I&#39;ve always been a big Nazgul fan, but a new card has caused me to take a look at the cavemen with the war-paint and rotten teeth. Don&#39;t get me wrong, I&#39;m still a Ringwraith-man. I just got tired of my second, third, fourth and fifth opponents "magically" knowing not to bid high against me (I hate scouters and blabber-mouths). That&#39;s not such a big deal anymore. Now that I have enough copies of certain cards, I&#8217;ve built a shadow side that counters, even kills, most of the new popular strategies as well as the old, and make most low bids largely irrelevant. <br>
<br>
Relying on Aragorn to protect Frodo? Exhaust him or add two burdens. Add two burdens? Ok, same choice again. How high did you bid? Hmm . . . a little tougher this time, huh? Suddenly you&#8217;re in the 3-5 burden range that activates some nasty special abilities (Orthanc Berserker, Enquea, Twilight Nelya, Toldea, Nazgul Sword). Ouch! And if you DO exhaust Aragorn and he has his bow . . . well, we&#8217;ll get to that soon. <br>
<br>
Have a Trust Me deck too? Too Great and Terrible x3 will take care of that strategy. Archery? Relentless Charge x4! Boromir and his Horn? Their Power is in Terror x3. Ally in the dead pile now? Uh oh, that little 2-cost Uruk Raider just got bigger AND fiercer. "This is what it sounds like . . . When Elves Cry . . ."<br>
<br>
Ok, so you aren&#8217;t relying on Aragorn, Gandalf, archery or Boromir and allies. Dwarves? Hobbits? Hope you weren&#8217;t counting on THEIR allies. Oh, and they need their conditions too, don&#8217;t they? This shadow doesn&#8217;t need any, so allow me to demonstrate Saruman&#8217;s Power! "Little Dead Hobbit . . . baby, you moved too fast . . ." <br>
<br>
Am I being too cheesy here? Probably. But this shadow can whack just about anything. Choke? Usually relies on Aragorn, and again, this is where Elrond/Ottar helps out big-time. No clogging here, even if you aren&#39;t using Aragorn, Gandalf, allies, archers or conditions. I don&#8217;t need Morgul Gates because all of my support cards, except for Saruman&#8217;s Power and Nazgul Sword, are 0-cost. They&#8217;re also maneuvers, so they happen before archery and before skirmish pumpers and abilities. Isn&#8217;t that cool? Discard? Hey, my deck&#8217;s a bit large anyway. I&#8217;ll just hold back on discarding myself. I&#39;ve got plenty of copies of my important stuff. You may actually help me.<br>
<br>
<br>
THE STAGE<br>
<br>
A little about sites: I obviously WANT people to use the Pony (burden AND Aragorn) even if I decide not to. It depends on my opening hand and how well it supports Gimli and Legolas. Hopefully, I&#8217;m going second and you&#8217;re hitting Nazgul Country anyway. Eregion Hills gives one more burden to spot (5 yet?) and the Glade&#8217;s a non-river/non-forest that doesn&#8217;t let an orc play cheap. The Great River IS great for me (no discard pile regen necessary for me, helps my fellowship) and the Shores are there for the twilight. The Summit just rocks here, but I SHOULD have finished first if they&#8217;re still kicking.<br>
<br>
<br>
Well, here&#39;s to looking forward to their making a weather condition called Saruman&#39;s (Purple) Rain. Thanks for reading this whole thing and thanks for any praise or constructive criticism. Please forgive my lame &#39;80s music jokes (hey, at least I had the decency to stay away from "Darling Nikki") and let me know if you&#8217;d like me to return the favor and review a deck of your own. Also, if you like the deck enough to try it, I&#8217;d love to hear how it does for you. D-mail me and we&#8217;ll discuss. Thanks again!   <br>
<br>
